  <span id="freeText16361858761413762368" style="display:none">I don't know whether to laugh or cry. Maybe both. This book stirred so many emotions in me that I don't think I can write a coherent review. Flannery O'Connor writes in such a fantastic way where you can't help but sympathize with unlikable characters and their plight in life. She's a master at blending the mundane with the surreal unlike any other author. The story follows Haze Motes and his goal to be a preacher of a different kind of church. A church without Christ. On the way he meets unforgettable characters and the more the story goes on, the more grotesque it gets. It's vintage Flannery O'Connor and I can't get enough of it. I initially thought that since she primarily writes short stories that this story wouldn't be able to sustain an entire novel but I was dead wrong. I wholeheartedly encourage anyone who is new to Flannery O'Connor to read this book and immediately buy her short story collection. I may be biased but I don't think you'll regret it. 5 out of 5</span>
